# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chief-compliance-officer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] An **account manager** (**AM**) is a person who works for a company and is responsible for the management of sales and relationships with particular customers.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] An account manager maintains the company's existing relationships with a client or group of clients, so that they will continue using the company for business.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] Account managers do not manage the daily running of the account.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] They manage the relationship with the client of the account(s) they are assigned to.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] Generally, a client will remain with one account manager throughout the account's duration.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] Account managers serve as the interface between customer service and the sales team in a company.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] They are assigned a company's existing client accounts.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] The purpose of being assigned particular clients is to create long term client relationships.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] The account manager serves to understand the customer's demands, plan how to meet these demands, and generate sales for the company as a result.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] The responsibilities of account managers can vary depending on the industry they work in, size of the company and nature of the business.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] Each customer account can vary in demands and an account manager may work with brand managers for one account and a media department for another.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] Account managers usually report directly to the account director or agency director of the activity and status of accounts and transactions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] An account manager may also manage a single account or a variety of accounts depending on the requirement of the company.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] Manage and solve conflicts with clients The Account Manager is expected to have specific information regarding the daily operations of the company and keep the Client updated.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] There are situations in which an account manager, for example in advertising firms, is responsible for more than one account and therefore looks after multiple clients.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] When account locations do not overlap the account manager can be placed at the divisional, district, or territory level.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] When a sales team has a senior sales manager, the account manager coordinates sales accounts from other departments or specialties.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] In this scenario, the sales team will work under the direct supervision of influencers and deciders instead of with a buyer.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] Global account managers and national account managers may work together in a hierarchical or matrix structure.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] The trend is to move responsibility for the major key accounts to the global level.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] A key account manager (KAM) is assigned to a company headquarters to oversee the account team assigned to a particular account.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] Key account management includes sales but also includes planning and managing the full relationship between a business and its most important customers.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] An account manager who works in this role will engage in a variety of tasks including project management, coordination, strategic planning, relationship management, negotiation, leadership and innovative development of opportunities, and keeping record of transactions of sale and purchase goods.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] The tasks may include working with product design and application, logistics, sales support, and marketing.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] The basic assumption for a key account management model is the correct classification of the key accounts.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] A basic model often used from 1950 to 1970 was the classification model of Webster.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] This model has been adapted by Milman and Wilson into a two-dimensional model and was paramount from 1970 to 1990.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] Bensaou has tested this model empirically by his research of carmakers in the United States and Japan and made revisions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] De Blick synthesized the adaptations into the 4S-model, a key account classification model.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] By the late 1990s, key account management spread to most B2B (business-to-business) models.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] Account managers can work for small or large companies either corporate, financial, retail, or government for instance.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] Any company with a specific set of clients they conduct business with, can employ an account manager.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] Account managers usually work in an office setting and can work more than 40 hours weekly.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] Travel is usually included in the job description.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] National or global account managers will very likely experience extra travel.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/account-manager] Although personality and an aptitude for sales is key, a degree in business, marketing, or related field is typically required and depending on the nature of the account, a background in marketing or media studies may be preferred.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] The **Bank Secrecy Act of 1970** (**BSA**), also known as the **Currency and Foreign Transactions Reporting Act**, is a U.S. law requiring financial institutions in the United States to assist U.S. government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Specifically, the act requires financial institutions to keep records of cash purchases of negotiable instruments, file reports if the daily aggregate exceeds $10,000, and report suspicious activity that may signify money laundering, tax evasion, or other criminal activities.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Notably, any individual leaving or entering the United States with $10,000 or more in currency must report it to Customs and Border Protection (CBP).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] This threshold has never been adjusted for inflation since 1970, which would be equivalent to $82,905 in 2025.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] The BSA is sometimes referred to as an anti-money laundering law (AML) or jointly as BSA/AML.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] The BSA was originally passed by the U.S.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Congress in 1970 and signed by President Richard Nixon into law on October 26, 1970.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Shortly after passage, several groups attempted to have the courts rule the law unconstitutional, claiming it violated both Fourth Amendment rights against unwarranted search and seizure, and Fifth Amendment rights of due process.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Several cases were combined before the Supreme Court in *California Bankers Assn. v.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] 21 (1974), which ruled that the Act did not violate the Constitution.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Until the 1980s, there was a "prolonged period of inaction", but financial institutions eventually complied with the BSA's reporting requirements.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] There was an attempt to include another amendment in 2018, called the Illicit Arts and Antiquities Trafficking Prevention Act (IAATP).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] As the name implies, its aim was to restrict illegal trafficking of art in the United States which has the highest rates of money laundering in the world.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] It was not passed in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] This was because the aim of the IAATP did not directly correspond with the aim of the BSA which, according to Congressman Luke Messer, sponsor of the bill, is to "counteract terrorist financing and crack down on terrorist organizations like ISIS".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] The **Bank Secrecy Act Advisory Group (BSAAG)** is a U.S. government–private sector forum established in 1992 by the U.S.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Its primary purpose is to enhance collaboration between financial institutions, law enforcement agencies, and regulators in implementing and improving anti-money laundering (AML) policies under the BSA.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Over the years, the BSAAG has played a crucial role in shaping U.S.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] AML regulations and ensuring that the BSA remains responsive to new financial technologies and criminal tactics.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Its recommendations have influenced major reforms, including those stemming from the USA PATRIOT Act and recent updates under the Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] The group supports the Treasury Department's enforcement of the Bank Secrecy Act, which is carried out by the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Membership is by invitation, and members typically serve three-year terms.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] BSA regulations require all financial institutions to submit five types of reports.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Individuals must file an individual filing requirement.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] A currency transaction report (CTR) reports cash transactions exceeding $10,000 in one business day, regardless of whether it's in one transaction or several cash transactions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] It is filed electronically with the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) and is identified as FinCEN Form 112 (formerly Form 104).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] CTRs include an individual's bank account number, name, address, and social security number.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] A single CTR filed for a client's account is usually of no concern to the authorities, while multiple CTRs from varying institutions or a SAR suggest that activity may be suspicious.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] A suspicious activity report (SAR) must report any cash transaction where the customer seems to be trying to avoid BSA reporting requirements by not filing CTR or monetary instrument log (MIL), for example.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] A SAR must also be filed if the customer's actions suggest that they are laundering money or otherwise violating federal criminal laws and committing wire transfer fraud, check fraud, or mysterious disappearances.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] These reports are filed with FinCEN and are identified as Treasury Department Form 90-22.47 and OCC Form 8010-9, 8010-1.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] This requirement and its accompanying implied gag order was added by the Annunzio-Wylie Anti-Money Laundering Act § 1517(b) (part of the Housing and Community Development Act of 1992, Pub.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] A financial institution is not allowed to inform a business or consumer that a SAR is being filed, and all the reports mandated by the BSA are exempt from disclosure under the Freedom of Information Act.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] U.S. citizens and residents with a financial interest in or authority over foreign bank accounts or "foreign financial accounts" with an aggregate value of $10,000 or more are required to file a Foreign Bank Account Report (FBAR) with the U.S.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] It is identified as FinCEN Form 114 (formerly Treasury Department Form 90-22.1).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Additionally, they must report the interest or dividend income from the accounts on Schedule B of the Form 1040 tax form and, if a higher threshold is exceeded, also report the amounts and interest on Form 8938.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Proponents of FBAR argue that it helps the United States deter financial crimes and encourage whistle-blowing for financial crimes, while critics argue that FBAR wastes time and money, "perversely discouraging compliance" without focusing on "likely criminal activity".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] A MIL must indicate cash purchases of monetary instruments, such as money orders, cashier's checks, and traveler's checks valued between $3,000 and $10,000.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] This form is required to be kept on record at the financial institution for at least five years, and produced at the request of examiners or audit to verify compliance.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] It is identified as FinCEN Form 105 Report.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Banks are required to file a Designation of Exempt Person (FinCEN Form 110) to designate an exempt customer for the purpose of CTR reporting under the BSA.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] In addition, banks use this form once every two years to renew exemptions for eligible non-listed business and payroll customers.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] It also requires any business receiving one or more related cash payments totaling more than $10,000 to file IRS/FinCEN Form 8300.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] There are heavy penalties for individuals and financial institutions that fail to file CTRs, MILs, or SARs.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] There are also penalties for banks who disclose to its client that it has filed a SAR about the client.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Penalties include heavy fines and prison sentences.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] IRC §6038D requires that all U.S. persons, individuals, corporations, partnerships, LLCs, and trusts, provide timely information regarding their foreign accounts, otherwise a $10,000 penalty will result for every month it is late (subject to a certain maximum penalty).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] In 1998, the Supreme Court ruled in *United States v.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Bajakajian and his family had tried to take $357,144 out of the United States in their luggage, and the government had seized it under the Bank Secrecy Act, which allows forfeiture of "any property, real or personal, involved in such offense".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] It was the first time the Supreme Court struck down the federal government's "aggressive use of forfeiture".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] In March 2010, Wachovia admitted to "serious and systemic" violations of the Bank Secrecy Act for laundering $378 billion between 2004 and 2007, the largest violation in terms of a dollar amount.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] It allowed Mexican and Colombian drug cartels to launder money through *casas de cambio* by willfully failing to set up an effective anti-money-laundering program.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] In 2022, Arthur Hayes, entrepreneur and co-founder and former CEO of cryptocurrency exchange BitMEX, pled guilty to Bank Secrecy Act violations and was sentenced to six months of home detention, two years of probation, and a $10 million fine.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] An entire industry has developed around providing software to analyze transactions in an attempt to identify transactions or patterns of transactions called structuring, which requires SAR filing.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Financial institutions are subject to penalties for failing to properly file CTRs and SARs, such as heavy fines and regulatory restrictions, including charter revocation.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] These software applications effectively monitor customer transactions on a daily basis and, using a customer's past transactions and account profile, provide a "whole picture" of the customer to the bank management.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] Transaction monitoring can include cash deposits and withdrawals, wire transfers, and ACH activity.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/bank-secrecy-act] In the banking industry, these applications are known as "BSA software" or "anti-money laundering software".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] A **board of directors** is a governing body that supervises the activities of a business, a nonprofit organization, or a government agency.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The powers, duties, and responsibilities of a board of directors are determined by government regulations (including the jurisdiction's corporate law) and the organization's own constitution and by-laws.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] These authorities may specify the number of members of the board, how they are to be chosen, and how often they are to meet.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In an organization with voting members, the board is accountable to, and may be subordinate to, the organization's full membership, which usually elect the members of the board.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In a stock corporation, non-executive directors are elected by the shareholders, and the board has ultimate responsibility for the management of the corporation.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In nations with codetermination (such as Germany and Sweden), the workers of a corporation elect a set fraction of the board's members.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The board of directors appoints the chief executive officer of the corporation and sets out the overall strategic direction.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In corporations with dispersed ownership, the identification and nomination of directors (that shareholders vote for or against) are often done by the board itself, leading to a high degree of self-perpetuation.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In a non-stock corporation with no general voting membership, the board is the supreme governing body of the institution, and its members are sometimes chosen by the board itself.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Other names include *board of directors and advisors*, *board of governors*, *board of managers*, *board of regents*, *board of trustees*, and *board of visitors*.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] It may also be called the *executive board*.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The legal responsibilities of boards and board members vary with the nature of the organization, and between jurisdictions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] For companies with shares publicly listed for negotiation, these responsibilities are typically much more rigorous and complex than for those of other types.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Typically, the board chooses one of its members to be the *chairman* (often now called the "chair" or "chairperson"), who holds whatever title is specified in the by-laws or articles of association.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] However, in membership organizations, the members elect the president of the organization and the president becomes the board chair, unless the by-laws say otherwise.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The directors of an organization are the persons who are members of its board.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Several specific terms categorize directors by the presence or absence of their other relationships to the organization.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Corporations may designate a former senior executive and ex-board member as an honorary board member, a position that does not carry any executive authority but represents recognition of the person's corporate governorship and performance.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] An inside director is a director who is also an employee, officer, chief executive, major shareholder, or someone similarly connected to the organization.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Inside directors represent the interests of the entity's stakeholders, and often have special knowledge of its inner workings, its financial or market position, and so on.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] An inside director who is employed as a manager or executive of the organization is sometimes referred to as an executive director (not to be confused with the title executive director sometimes used for the CEO position in some organizations).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Executive directors often have a specified area of responsibility in the organization, such as finance, marketing, human resources, or production.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] An outside director is a member of the board who is not otherwise employed by or engaged with the organization, and does not represent any of its stakeholders.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] A typical example is a director who is president of a firm in a different industry.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Outside directors are not employees of the company or affiliated with it in any other way.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Outside directors bring outside experience and perspectives to the board.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] For example, for a company that serves a domestic market only, the presence of CEOs from global multinational corporations as outside directors can help to provide insights on export and import opportunities and international trade options.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] One of the arguments for having outside directors is that they can keep a watchful eye on the inside directors and on the way the organization is run.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Outside directors are unlikely to tolerate "insider dealing" between inside directors, as outside directors do not benefit from the company or organization.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Outside directors are often useful in handling disputes between inside directors, or between shareholders and the board.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] They are thought to be advantageous because they can be objective and present little risk of conflict of interest.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] On the other hand, they might lack familiarity with the specific issues connected to the organization's governance, and they might not know about the industry or sector in which the organization is operating.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Individual directors often serve on more than one board.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] This practice results in an interlocking directorate, where a relatively small number of individuals have significant influence over many important entities.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] This situation can have important corporate, social, economic, and legal consequences, and has been the subject of significant research.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The science of this process has been slow to develop due to the secretive nature of the way most companies run their boards, however some standardization is beginning to develop.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Some who are pushing for this standardization in the US are the National Association of Corporate Directors, McKinsey and The Board Group.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] A board of directors conducts its meetings according to the rules and procedures contained in its governing documents.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] These procedures may allow the board to conduct its business by conference call or other electronic means.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] They may also specify how a quorum is to be determined.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The responsibilities of a board of directors vary depending on the nature and type of business entity and the laws applying to the entity (see types of business entity).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] There are numerous types of business entities available throughout the world such as a corporation, limited liability company, cooperative, business trust, partnership, private limited company, and public limited company.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Much of what has been written about boards of directors relates to boards of directors of business entities actively traded on public markets.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] More recently, however, material is becoming available for boards of private and closely held businesses including family businesses.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] A board-only organization is one whose board is self-appointed, rather than being accountable to a base of members through elections; or in which the powers of the membership are extremely limited.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The amount of powers and authority delegated to the board depend on the bylaws and rules of the particular organization.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Some organizations place matters exclusively in the board's control while in others, the general membership retains full power and the board can only make recommendations.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The setup of a board of directors varies widely across organizations and may include provisions that are applicable to corporations, in which the "shareholders" are the members of the organization.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] A difference may be that the membership elects the officers of the organization, such as the president and the secretary, and the officers become members of the board in addition to the directors and retain those duties on the board.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The directors may also be classified as officers in this situation.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] There may also be ex-officio members of the board, or persons who are members due to another position that they hold.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] These ex-officio members have all the same rights as the other board members.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Members of the board may be removed before their term is complete.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Details on how they can be removed are usually provided in the bylaws.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] If the bylaws do not contain such details, the section on disciplinary procedures in *Robert's Rules of Order* may be used.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In a publicly held company, directors are elected to represent and are legally obligated as fiduciaries to represent owners of the company—the shareholders/stockholders.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In this capacity they establish policies and make decisions on issues such as whether there is a dividend and how much it is, stock options distributed to employees, and the hiring/firing and compensation of upper management.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Theoretically, the control of a company is divided between two bodies: the board of directors, and the shareholders in general meeting.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In practice, the amount of power exercised by the board varies with the type of company.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In small private companies, the directors and the shareholders are normally the same people, and thus there is no real division of power.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Another feature of boards of directors in large public companies is that the board tends to have more *de facto* power.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Most shareholders do not attend shareholder meetings, but rather cast proxy votes via mail, phone, or internet, thus allowing the board to vote for them.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] However, proxy votes are not a total delegation of the voting power, as the board must vote the proxy shares as directed by their owner even when it contradicts the board's views.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In addition, many shareholders vote to accept all recommendations of the board rather than try to get involved in management, since each shareholder's power, as well as interest and information is so small.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Larger institutional investors also grant the board proxies.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The large number of shareholders also makes it hard for them to organize.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] However, there have been moves recently to try to increase shareholder activism among both institutional investors and individuals with small shareholdings.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] A contrasting view is that in large public companies it is upper management and not boards that wield practical power, because boards delegate nearly all of their power to the top executive employees, adopting their recommendations almost without fail.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] As a practical matter, executives even choose the directors, with shareholders normally following management recommendations and voting for them.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In most cases, serving on a board is not a career unto itself.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] For major corporations, the board members are usually professionals or leaders in their field.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In the case of outside directors, they are often senior leaders of other organizations.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Nevertheless, board members often receive remunerations amounting to hundreds of thousands of dollars per year since they often sit on the boards of several companies.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Inside directors are usually not paid for sitting on a board, but the duty is instead considered part of their larger job description.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Outside directors are usually paid for their services.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] These remunerations vary between corporations, but usually consist of a yearly or monthly salary, additional compensation for each meeting attended, stock options, and various other benefits. such as travel, hotel and meal expenses for the board meetings.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Academic research has identified different types of board directors.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Their characteristics and experiences shape their role and performance.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] For instance, directors with multiple mandates are often referred to as busy directors.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Their monitoring performance is considered to be comparatively weak due to the limited time they can dedicate to this task.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Overconfident directors are found to pay higher premiums in corporate acquisitions and make worse takeover choices.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Locally rooted directors tend to be overrepresented and lack international experience, which can lead to lower valuations, especially in internationally oriented firms.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Directors' military experience is associated with rigorous monitoring and improved corporate governance.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In some European and Asian countries, there are two separate boards, an executive board (or management board) for day-to-day business and a supervisory board (elected by the shareholders and employees) for supervising the executive board.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In these countries, the chairman of the supervisory board is equivalent to the chairman of a single-tier board, while the chairman of the management board is reckoned as the company's CEO or managing director.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] These two roles are always held by different people.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] This ensures a distinction between management by the executive board and governance by the supervisory board and allows for clear lines of authority.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The aim is to prevent a conflict of interest and too much power being concentrated in the hands of one person.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] There is a strong parallel here with the structure of government, where parliament (the supervisory board) oversees a cabinet of ministers (management officials, comprising the executive board) led by a head of government (CEO).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Board structures and procedures vary both within and among OECD countries.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Some countries have two-tier boards that separate the supervisory function and the management function into different bodies.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Such systems typically have a "supervisory board" composed of nonexecutive board members and a "management board" composed entirely of executives.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Other countries have "unitary" boards, which bring together executive and non-executive board members.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In some countries there is also an additional statutory body for audit purposes.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The OECD Principles are intended to be sufficiently general to apply to whatever board structure is charged with the functions of governing the enterprise and monitoring management.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The development of a separate board of directors to manage/govern/oversee a company has occurred incrementally and indefinitely over legal history.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Until the end of the 19th century, it seems to have been generally assumed that the general meeting (of all shareholders) was the supreme organ of a company, and that the board of directors merely acted as an agent of the company subject to the control of the shareholders in general meeting.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The new approach did not secure immediate approval, but it was endorsed by the House of Lords in *Quin & Axtens v Salmon* [1909] AC 442 and has since received general acceptance.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Under English law, successive versions of Table A have reinforced the norm that, unless the directors are acting contrary to the law or the provisions of the Articles, the powers of conducting the management and affairs of the company are vested in them.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] It has been remarked that this development in the law was somewhat surprising at the time, as the relevant provisions in Table A (as it was then) seemed to contradict this approach rather than to endorse it.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The age of board members has become a notable trend across global stock exchanges, reflecting an increasingly older demographic in leadership roles.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] As of 2025, the average age of board members of companies listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange stands at 62.2 years, while the United Kingdom reports an average of 60.1 years, Germany 59.3 years, South Korea 59 years, and Hong Kong 54.9 years.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] New York Stock Exchange companies exhibit the highest average age, at 62.9 years.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In response to this aging trend, some firms, particularly those in entertainment and trend-driven sectors, have actively sought to appoint younger board members.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] An example is Sanrio, the Japanese company behind the Hello Kitty franchise, which reduced the average age of its board from 68 years in 2020 to 51 years by 2024, signaling a deliberate intergenerational shift in governance.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In most legal systems, the appointment and removal of directors is voted upon by the shareholders in general meeting or through a proxy statement.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] For publicly traded companies in the U.S., the directors which are available to vote on are largely selected by either the board as a whole or a nominating committee.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Shareholder nominations can only occur at the general meeting itself or through the prohibitively expensive process of mailing out ballots separately; in May 2009 the SEC proposed a new rule allowing shareholders meeting certain criteria to add nominees to the proxy statement.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In countries with co-determination, a fixed fraction of the board is elected by the corporation's workers.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Directors may also leave office by resignation or death.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In some legal systems, directors may also be removed by a resolution of the remaining directors (in some countries they may only do so "with cause"; in others the power is unrestricted).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Some jurisdictions also permit the board of directors to appoint directors, either to fill a vacancy which arises on resignation or death, or as an addition to the existing directors.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In practice, it can be quite difficult to remove a director by a resolution in general meeting.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In many legal systems, the director has a right to receive special notice of any resolution to remove them; the company must often supply a copy of the proposal to the director, who is usually entitled to be heard by the meeting.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The director may require the company to circulate any representations that they wish to make.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Furthermore, the director's contract of service will usually entitle them to compensation if they are removed, and may often include a generous "golden parachute" which also acts as a deterrent to removal.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] A 2010 study examined how corporate shareholders voted in director elections in the United States.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] It found that directors received fewer votes from shareholders when their companies performed poorly, had excess CEO compensation, or had poor shareholder protection.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Also, directors received fewer votes when they did not regularly attend board meetings or received negative recommendations from a proxy advisory firm.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The study also shows that companies often improve their corporate governance by removing poison pills or classified boards and by reducing excessive CEO pay after their directors receive low shareholder support.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Board accountability to shareholders is a recurring issue.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In September 2010, *The New York Times* noted that several directors who had overseen companies which had failed in the 2008 financial crisis had found new positions as directors.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The SEC sometimes imposes a ban (a "D&O bar") on serving on a board as part of its fraud cases, and one of these was upheld in 2013.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The exercise by the board of directors of its powers usually occurs in board meetings.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Most legal systems require sufficient notice to be given to all directors of these meetings, and that a quorum must be present before any business may be conducted.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In most common law countries, the powers of the board are vested in the board as a whole, and not in the individual directors.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] However, in instances an individual director may still bind the company by their acts by virtue of their ostensible authority (see also: the rule in *Turquand's Case*).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Because directors exercise control and management over the organization, but organizations are (in theory) run for the benefit of the shareholders, the law imposes strict duties on directors in relation to the exercise of their duties.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The duties imposed on directors are fiduciary duties, similar to those that the law imposes on those in similar positions of trust: agents and trustees.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The duties apply to each director separately, while the powers apply to the board jointly.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Also, the duties are owed to the company itself, and not to any other entity.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] This does not mean that directors can never stand in a fiduciary relationship to the individual shareholders; they may well have such a duty in certain circumstances.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Directors must exercise their powers for a proper purpose.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] While in many instances an improper purpose is readily evident, such as a director looking to enrich themselves or divert an investment opportunity to a relative, such breaches usually involve a breach of the director's duty to act in good faith.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Greater difficulties arise where the director, while acting in good faith, is serving a purpose that is not regarded by the law as proper.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The seminal authority in the United Kingdom in relation to what amounts to a proper purpose is the Supreme Court decision in Eclairs Group Ltd v JKX Oil & Gas plc (2015).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The case concerned the powers of directors under the articles of association of the company to disenfranchise voting rights attached to shares for failure to properly comply with notice served on the shareholders.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Prior to that case the leading authority was *Howard Smith Ltd v Ampol Ltd* [1974] AC 821.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The case concerned the power of the directors to issue new shares.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] It was alleged that the directors had issued many new shares purely to deprive a particular shareholder of his voting majority.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] If so, the mere fact that an incidental result (even if it was a desired consequence) was that a shareholder lost their majority, or a takeover bid was defeated, this would not itself make the share issue improper.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] But if the sole purpose was to destroy a voting majority, or block a takeover bid, that would be an improper purpose.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Not all jurisdictions recognised the "proper purpose" duty as separate from the "good faith" duty however.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Directors cannot, without the consent of the company, fetter their discretion in relation to the exercise of their powers, and cannot bind themselves to vote in a particular way at future board meetings.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] This is so even if there is no improper motive or purpose, and no personal advantage to the director.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] This does not mean, however, that the board cannot agree to the company entering into a contract which binds the company to a certain course, even if certain actions in that course will require further board approval, such as issuing bonds.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The company remains bound, but the directors retain the discretion to vote against taking the future actions (although that may involve a breach by the company of the contract that the board previously approved).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] As fiduciaries, the directors may not put themselves in a position where their interests and duties conflict with the duties that they owe to the company.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The law takes the view that good faith must not only be done, but must be manifestly seen to be done, and zealously patrols the conduct of directors in this regard; and will not allow directors to escape liability by asserting that their decisions were in fact well founded.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] By definition, where a director enters into a transaction with a company, there is a conflict between the director's interest (to enrich themselves with the transaction) and their duty to the company (to ensure that the company gets as much as it can out of the transaction).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In some places, this rule is so strictly enforced that, even where the conflict of interest or conflict of duty is purely hypothetical, the directors can be forced to disgorge all personal gains arising from it.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] "A corporate body can only act by agents, and it is, of course, the duty of those agents so to act as best to promote the interests of the corporation whose affairs they are conducting.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Such agents have duties to discharge of a fiduciary nature towards their principal.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] , with the interests of those whom he is bound to protect...
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] However, in many jurisdictions the members of the company are permitted to ratify transactions which would otherwise fall foul of this principle.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] It is also largely accepted in most jurisdictions that this principle can be overridden in the company's constitution.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] In many countries, there is also a statutory duty to declare interests in relation to any transactions, and the director can be fined for failing to make disclosure.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Directors must not, without the informed consent of the company, use for their own profit the company's assets, opportunities, or information.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] This prohibition is much less flexible than the prohibition against the transactions with the company, and attempts to circumvent it using provisions in the articles have met with limited success.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] And accordingly, the directors were required to disgorge the profits that they made, and the shareholders received their windfall.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The decision has been followed in several subsequent cases, and is now regarded as settled law.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Directors cannot compete directly with the company without a conflict of interest arising.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Similarly, they should not act as directors of competing companies, as their duties to each company would then conflict with each other.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Traditionally, the level of care and skill which has to be demonstrated by a director has been framed largely with reference to the non-executive director.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] However, a more modern approach has since developed, and in *Dorchester Finance Co Ltd v Stebbing* [1989] BCLC 498 the court held that the rule in *Equitable Fire* related only to skill, and not to diligence.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] This was a dual subjective and objective test, and one deliberately pitched at a higher level.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] More recently, it has been suggested that both the tests of skill and diligence should be assessed objectively and subjectively; in the United Kingdom, the statutory provisions relating to directors' duties in the new Companies Act 2006 have been codified on this basis.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Historically, directors' duties have been owed almost exclusively to the company and its members, and the board was expected to exercise its powers for the financial benefit of the company.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] However, more recently there have been attempts to "soften" the position, and provide for more scope for directors to act as good corporate citizens.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] This represents a considerable departure from the traditional notion that directors' duties are owed only to the company.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The changes have therefore been the subject of some criticism.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The adoption of technology that facilitates the meeting preparation and execution of directors continues to grow.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Board directors are increasingly leveraging this technology to communicate and collaborate within a secure environment to access meeting materials, communicate with each other, and execute their governance responsibilities.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] This trend is particularly acute in the United States where a robust market of early adopters garnered acceptance of board software by organizations resulting in higher penetration of the board portal services in the region.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Most companies have weak mechanisms for bringing the voice of society into the board room.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] They rely on personalities who were not appointed for their understanding of societal issues.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Often they give limited focus (both through time and financial resource) to issues of corporate responsibility and sustainability.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] A social board has society designed into its structure.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] It elevates the voice of society through specialist appointments to the board and mechanisms that empower innovation from within the organisation.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Social boards align themselves with themes that are important to society.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] These may include measuring worker pay ratios, linking personal social and environmental objectives to remuneration, integrated reporting, fair tax and B-Corp certification.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Social boards recognise that they are part of society and that they require more than a licence to operate to succeed.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] They balance short-term shareholder pressure against long-term value creation, managing the business for a plurality of stakeholders including employees, shareholders, supply chains and civil society.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] India has no legislative equivalent to Sarbanes–Oxley Act (given below), though Clause 49 of the SEBI Listing Agreement provides relevant rules.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] India adopted this new corporate governance standard under Article 49 of the Listing Agreement on 31 December 2005, which is mandatory for all listed companies.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] This provision mandates certain governance practices for companies listed on Indian stock exchanges.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Key provisions under clause 49 include those under which top executives like CEOs and CFOs must verify the effectiveness and accuracy of financial statements.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] After the Satyam scandal in 2009, internal financial controls gained importance in India.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The Companies Act, 2013 introduced internal financial controls imposing specific responsibilities on the board, audit committee, management and others.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The Sarbanes–Oxley Act of 2002 has introduced new standards of accountability on boards of U.S. companies or companies listed on U.S. stock exchanges.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Under the act, directors risk large fines and prison sentences in the case of accounting crimes.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Internal control is now the direct responsibility of directors.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The vast majority of companies covered by the act have hired internal auditors to ensure that the company adheres to required standards of internal control.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The internal auditors are required by law to report directly to an audit board, consisting of directors more than half of whom are outside directors, one of whom is a "financial expert".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The law requires companies listed on the major stock exchanges (NYSE, NASDAQ) to have a majority of independent directors—directors who are not otherwise employed by the firm or in a business relationship with it.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] According to the Corporate Library's study, the average size of publicly traded company's board is 9.2 members, and most boards range from 3 to 31 members.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] According to Investopedia, some analysts think the ideal size is seven.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] State law may specify a minimum number of directors, maximum number of directors, and qualifications for directors (e.g. whether board members must be individuals or may be business entities).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] While a board may have several committees, two—the compensation committee and audit committee—are critical and must be made up of at least three independent directors and no inside directors.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Other common committees in boards are nominating, governance and investment.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Directors of Fortune 500 companies received median pay of $234,000 in 2011.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] A 2011 study by the National Association of Corporate Directors in the United States estimated that directors averaged 4.3 hours a week on board work.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Surveys have indicated that about 20% of nonprofit foundations pay their board members, and 2% of American nonprofit organizations do.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] 80% of nonprofit organizations require board members to personally contribute to the organization.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] As of 2007, this percentage had increased in recent years.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] According to John Gillespie, a former investment banker and co-author of a book critical of boards, "Far too much of their time has been for check-the-box and cover-your-behind activities rather than real monitoring of executives and providing strategic advice on behalf of shareholders".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] At the same time, scholars have found that individual directors have a large effect on major corporate initiatives such as mergers and acquisitions and cross-border investments.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] According to the International Institute of Management, the rise in investor dissatisfaction, class-action lawsuits and shareholder activism has resulted in more attention directed toward the board of directors and the lack of corporate governance accountability.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Shareholders' complaints include issues such as excessive executive compensation and passive participation (lack of proper governance) of the board members.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The journal paper cites examples of underperforming CEOs of Fortune 500 companies who took compensation and retirement package in hundreds of millions of dollars while the stock price of their companies lost billions of dollars.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The research proposes institutionalizing a standardized board evaluation framework to help balance between the executive compensation and protecting the interest of shareholders.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] The issue of gender representation on corporate boards of directors has been the subject of much criticism in recent years.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] Governments and corporations have responded with measures such as legislation mandating gender quotas and comply or explain systems to address the disproportionality of gender representation on corporate boards.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/board-of-directors] A study of the French corporate elite has found that certain social classes are also disproportionately represented on boards, with those from the upper and, especially, upper-middle classes tending to dominate.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Business ethics refers to contemporary organizational standards, principles, sets of values, and norms that govern the actions and behavior of individuals in a business organization.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Business ethics has two dimensions: normative business ethics and descriptive business ethics.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] As a corporate practice and a career specialization, the field is primarily normative.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Academics attempting to understand business behavior employ descriptive methods.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The range and quantity of business ethical issues reflect the interaction of profit-maximizing behavior with non-economic concerns.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Interest in business ethics accelerated dramatically during the 1980s and 1990s, both within major corporations and within academia.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] For example, most major corporations today promote their commitment to non-economic values under headings such as ethics codes and social responsibility charters.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Ethics implicitly regulates areas and details of behavior that lie beyond governmental control.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The emergence of large corporations with limited relationships and sensitivity to the communities in which they operate accelerated the development of formal ethics regimes.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Maintaining an ethical status is the responsibility of the manager of the business.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Business ethics reflect the norms of each historical period.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] As time passes, norms evolve, causing accepted behaviors to become objectionable.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Business ethics and the resulting behavior evolved as well.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Business was involved in slavery, colonialism, and the Cold War.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The term 'business ethics' came into common use in the United States in the early 1970s.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] By the mid-1980s, at least 500 courses in business ethics reached 40,000 students, using some twenty textbooks and at least ten casebooks supported by professional societies, centers and journals of business ethics.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The Society for Business Ethics was founded in 1980.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] European business schools adopted business ethics after 1987, commencing with the European Business Ethics Network.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] In 1982, the first single-authored books in the field appeared.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Firms began highlighting their ethical stature in the late 1980s and early 1990s, possibly in an attempt to distance themselves from the business scandals of the day, such as the savings and loan crisis.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The concept of business ethics caught the attention of academics, media and business firms by the end of the Cold War.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] However, criticism of business practices was attacked for infringing on the freedom of entrepreneurs and critics were accused of supporting communists.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] This scuttled the discourse of business ethics both in the media and academia.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The Defense Industry Initiative on Business Ethics and Conduct (DII) was created to support corporate ethical conduct.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] This era began the belief and support of self-regulation and free trade, which lifted tariffs and barriers and allowed businesses to merge and divest in an increasingly global atmosphere.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] One of the earliest written treatments of business ethics is found in the *Tirukkuṛaḷ*, a Tamil book dated variously from 300 BCE to the 7th century CE and attributed to Thiruvalluvar.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Many verses discuss business ethics, in particular, verse 113, adapting to a changing environment in verses 474, 426, and 140, learning the intricacies of different tasks in verses 462 and 677.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Business ethics reflects the philosophy of business, which one of those aims is to determine the fundamental purposes of a company.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Business purpose expresses the company's reason for existing.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Modern discussion on the purpose of business has been freshened by views from thinkers such as Richard R.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Ellesworth, Peter Drucker, and Nikos Mourkogiannis: Earlier views, such as Milton Friedman's, held that the purpose of a business organization is to make a profit for shareholders.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Nevertheless, the purpose of maximizing shareholders' wealth often "fails to energize employees".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] On the other hand, if a company's purpose is to maximize shareholder returns, then sacrificing profits for other concerns is a violation of its fiduciary responsibility.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Corporate entities are legal persons but this does not mean they are legally entitled to all of the rights and liabilities of natural persons.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Ethics are the rules or standards that govern our decisions on a daily basis.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Many consider "ethics" with conscience or a simplistic sense of "right" and "wrong".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Others would say that ethics is an internal code that governs an individual's conduct, ingrained into each person by family, faith, tradition, community, laws, and personal mores.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Corporations and professional organizations, particularly licensing boards, generally will have a written code of ethics that governs standards of professional conduct expected of all in the field.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] "Law" and "ethics" are not synonymous, nor are the "legal" and "ethical" courses of action in a given situation necessarily the same.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Statutes and regulations passed by legislative bodies and administrative boards set forth the "law".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Slavery was once legal in the US, but one certainly would not say enslaving another was an "ethical" act.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Economist Milton Friedman wrote that corporate executives' "responsibility ... generally will be to make as much money as possible while conforming to their basic rules of the society, both those embodied in law and those embodied in ethical custom".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Friedman also said, "the only entities who can have responsibilities are individuals ...
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] A business cannot have responsibilities.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] So the question is, do corporate executives, provided they stay within the law, have responsibilities in their business activities other than to make as much money for their stockholders as possible?
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] And my answer to that is, no, they do not." This view is known as the Friedman doctrine.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] A multi-country 2011 survey found support for this view among the "informed public" ranging from 30 to 80%.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Ronald Duska and Jacques Cory have described Friedman's argument as consequentialist or utilitarian rather than pragmatic: Friedman's argument implies that unrestrained corporate freedom would benefit the most people in the long term.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] So Friedman was wrong that making a profit is the only concern of business, Duska argued.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Peter Drucker once said, "There is neither a separate ethics of business nor is one needed", implying that standards of personal ethics cover all business situations.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] However, Drucker in another instance said that the ultimate responsibility of company directors is not to harm—*primum non nocere*.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Philosopher and author Ayn Rand has put forth her idea of rational egoism, which also applies to business ethics.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] She stresses that the position of the entrepreneur, who has to be responsible for his own happiness and the business is a means to said happiness, where the entrepreneur is not required to serve the interest of anyone else and no one is entitled to his/her work.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Another view of business is that it must exhibit corporate social responsibility (CSR): an umbrella term indicating that an ethical business must act as a responsible citizen of the communities in which it operates, even at the cost of profits or other goals.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] In the US and most other nations, corporate entities are legally treated as persons in some respects.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] For example, they can hold title to property, sue and be sued and are subject to taxation, although their free speech rights are limited.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] This can be interpreted to imply that they have independent ethical responsibilities.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Duska argued that stakeholders expect a business to be ethical and that violating that expectation must be counterproductive for the business.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Ethical issues include the rights and duties between a company and its employees, suppliers, customers and neighbors, its fiduciary responsibility to its shareholders.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Issues concerning relations between different companies include hostile takeovers and industrial espionage.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Related issues include corporate governance, corporate social entrepreneurship, political contributions, legal issues such as the ethical debate over introducing a crime of corporate manslaughter, and the marketing of corporations' ethics policies.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] According to research published by the Institute of Business Ethics and Ipsos MORI in late 2012, the three major areas of public concern regarding business ethics in Britain are executive pay, corporate tax avoidance and bribery and corruption.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The ethical standards of an entire organization can be damaged if a corporate psychopath is in charge.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] This will affect not only the company and its outcome but also the employees who work under a corporate psychopath.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The way a corporate psychopath can rise in a company is by their manipulation, scheming, and bullying.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] They do this in a way that can hide their true character and intentions within a company.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Fundamentally, finance is a social science discipline.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The discipline borders behavioral economics, sociology, economics, accounting and management.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] It concerns technical issues such as the mix of debt and equity, dividend policy, the evaluation of alternative investment projects, options, futures, swaps, and other derivatives, portfolio diversification and many others.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Finance is often mistaken by people to be a discipline free from ethical burdens.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The 2008 financial crisis caused critics to challenge the ethics of the executives in charge of U.S. and European financial institutions and financial regulatory bodies.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Finance ethics is overlooked for another reason—issues in finance are often addressed as matters of law rather than ethics.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Aristotle said, "the end and purpose of the polis is the good life".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Adam Smith characterized the good life in terms of material goods and intellectual and moral excellences of character.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] However, a section of economists influenced by the ideology of neoliberalism interpreted the objective of economics to be the maximization of economic growth through accelerated consumption and production of goods and services.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Neoliberal ideology promoted finance from its position as a component of economics to its core.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Proponents of the ideology hold that unrestricted financial flows, if redeemed from the shackles of "financial repressions", best help impoverished nations to grow.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The theory holds that open financial systems accelerate economic growth by encouraging foreign capital inflows, thereby enabling higher levels of savings, investment, employment, productivity and "welfare", along with containing corruption.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Neoliberals recommended that governments open their financial systems to the global market with minimal regulation over capital flows.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The recommendations, however, met with criticisms from various schools of ethical philosophy.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Some pragmatic ethicists found these claims to be unfalsifiable and a priori, although neither of these makes the recommendations false or unethical per se.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Raising economic growth to the highest value necessarily means that welfare is subordinate, although advocates dispute this, saying that economic growth provides more welfare than known alternatives.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Since history shows that neither regulated nor unregulated firms always behave ethically, neither regime offers an ethical panacea.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Neoliberal recommendations to developing countries to unconditionally open up their economies to transnational finance corporations were fiercely contested by some ethicists.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The claim that deregulation and the opening up of economies would reduce corruption was also contested.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Dobson observes, "a rational agent is simply one who pursues personal material advantage ad infinitum.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] In essence, to be rational in finance is to be individualistic, materialistic, and competitive.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Business is a game played by individuals, as with all games, the object is to win, and winning is measured in terms solely of material wealth.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Within the discipline, this rationality concept is never questioned, and has indeed become the theory-of-the-firm's sine qua non".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Financial ethics, is in this view, a mathematical function of shareholder wealth.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Such simplifying assumptions were once necessary for the construction of mathematically robust models.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] However, signalling theory and agency theory extended the paradigm to greater realism.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Fairness in trading practices, trading conditions, financial contracting, sales practices, consultancy services, tax payments, internal audit, external audit and executive compensation also fall under the umbrella of finance and accounting.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Particular corporate ethical/legal abuses include: creative accounting, earnings management, misleading financial analysis, insider trading, securities fraud, bribery/kickbacks and facilitation payments.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Outside of corporations, bucket shops and forex scams are criminal manipulations of financial markets.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Cases include accounting scandals, Enron, WorldCom and Satyam.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Human resource management occupies the sphere of activity of recruitment selection, orientation, performance appraisal, training and development, industrial relations and health and safety issues.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Business Ethicists differ in their orientation towards labor ethics.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Some assess human resource policies according to whether they support an egalitarian workplace and the dignity of labor.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Issues including employment itself, privacy, compensation in accord with comparable worth, collective bargaining (and/or its opposite) can be seen either as inalienable rights or as negotiable.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Discrimination by age (preferring the young or the old), gender/sexual harassment, race, religion, disability, weight and attractiveness.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] A common approach to remedying discrimination is affirmative action.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Once hired, employees have the right to the occasional cost-of-living increases, as well as raises based on merit.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Promotions, however, are not a right, and there are often fewer openings than qualified applicants.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] It may seem unfair if an employee who has been with a company longer is passed over for a promotion, but it is not unethical.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] It is only unethical if the employer did not give the employee proper consideration or used improper criteria for the promotion.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Each employer should know the distinction between what is unethical and what is illegal.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] If an action is illegal, it is breaking the law, but if an action seems morally incorrect, that is unethical.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] In the workplace, what is unethical does not mean illegal and should follow the guidelines put in place by OSHA (Occupational Safety and Health Administration), EEOC (Equal Employment Opportunity Commission), and other law-binding entities.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Potential employees have ethical obligations to employers, involving intellectual property protection and whistle-blowing.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Employers must consider workplace safety, which may involve modifying the workplace or providing appropriate training or hazard disclosure.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] This differentiates based on the location and type of work that is taking place and may require compliance with the standards to protect employees and non-employees under workplace safety.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Larger economic issues such as immigration, trade policy, globalization and trade unionism affect workplaces and have an ethical dimension, but are often beyond the purview of individual companies.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Trade unions, for example, may push employers to establish due process for workers, but may also cause job loss by demanding unsustainable compensation and work rules.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Among the many people management strategies that companies employ are a "soft" approach that regards employees as a source of creative energy and participants in workplace decision-making, a "hard" version explicitly focused on control and Theory Z that emphasizes philosophy, culture and consensus.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Some studies claim that sustainable success requires a humanely treated and satisfied workforce.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] In the procurement field, ethical behaviour includes adherence to the principle of fairness, avoidance of preferential treatment, and the elimination of malpractice in relation to suppliers and their workforces.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The Chartered Institute of Procurement & Supply, which provides ethical procurement assessment for its members, notes that "it's important to recognise that being ethical isn't just within the business community, but consumers can also make ethical choices in their buying decisions".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Marketing ethics came of age only as late as the 1990s.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Marketing ethics was approached from ethical perspectives of virtue or virtue ethics, deontology, consequentialism, pragmatism and relativism.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Ethics in marketing deals with the principles, values and/or ideas by which marketers (and marketing institutions) ought to act.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Marketing ethics is also a contested terrain, beyond the previously described issue of potential conflicts between profitability and other concerns.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] According to Borgerson and Schroeder (2008), marketing can influence individuals' perceptions of and interactions with other people, implying an ethical responsibility to avoid distorting those perceptions and interactions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Marketing ethics involves pricing practices, including illegal actions such as price fixing and legal actions, including price discrimination and price skimming.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Certain promotional activities have drawn fire, including greenwashing, bait and switch, shilling, viral marketing, spam (electronic), pyramid schemes and multi-level marketing.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Advertising has raised objections about attack ads, subliminal messages, sex in advertising and marketing in schools.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Scholars in business and management have paid much attention to the ethical issues in the different forms of relationships between organizations such as buyer-supplier relationships, networks, alliances, or joint ventures.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Drawing in particular on transaction cost theory and agency theory, they note the risk of opportunistic and unethical practices between partners through, for instance, shirking, poaching, and other deceitful behaviors.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] In turn, research on inter-organizational relationships has observed the role of formal and informal mechanisms to both prevent unethical practices and mitigate their consequences.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] It especially discusses the importance of formal contracts and relational norms between partners to manage ethical issues.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Being the most important element of a business, stakeholders' main concern is to determine whether or not the business is behaving ethically or unethically.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The business's actions and decisions should be primarily ethical before they become an ethical or even legal issue.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] This area of business ethics usually deals with the duties of a company to ensure that products and production processes do not needlessly cause harm.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Since a few goods and services can be produced and consumed with zero risks, determining the ethical course can be difficult.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] In some cases, consumers demand products that harm them, such as tobacco products.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Production may have environmental impacts, including pollution, habitat destruction and urban sprawl.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The downstream effects of technologies, such as nuclear power, genetically modified food and mobile phones, may not be well understood.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] While the precautionary principle may prohibit introducing new technology whose consequences are not fully understood, that principle would have prohibited the newest technology introduced since the Industrial Revolution.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Product testing protocols have been attacked for violating the rights of both humans and animals.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Some sources that provide information on companies that are environmentally responsible or do not test on animals.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The etymological root of property is the Latin *proprius*, which refers to 'nature', 'quality', 'one's own', 'special characteristic', 'proper', 'intrinsic', 'inherent', 'regular', 'normal', 'genuine', 'thorough, complete, perfect' etc.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The word property is value-loaded and associated with the personal qualities of propriety and respectability, and it also implies questions relating to ownership.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] A 'proper' person owns and is true to herself or himself, and is thus genuine, perfect and pure.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Modern discourse on property emerged by the turn of the 17th century within theological discussions of that time.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] For instance, John Locke justified property rights, saying that God had made "the earth, and all inferior creatures, [in] common to all men".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] In 1802, utilitarian Jeremy Bentham stated, "property and law are born together and die together".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] One argument for property ownership is that it enhances individual liberty by extending the line of non-interference by the state or others around the person.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Seen from this perspective, property rights are absolute and property has a special and distinctive character that precedes its legal protection.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Blackstone conceptualized property as the "sole and despotic dominion which one man claims and exercises over the external things of the world, in total exclusion of the right of any other individual in the universe".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] During the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, slavery spread to European colonies, including America, where colonial legislatures defined the legal status of slaves as a form of property.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Combined with theological justification, the property was taken to be essentially natural, ordained by God.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Wiecek says, "Yet slavery was more clearly and explicitly established under the Constitution than it had been under the Articles".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] In an 1857 judgment, US Supreme Court Chief Justice Roger B.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Neoliberals hold that private property rights are a non-negotiable natural right.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Rose finds, "'Property' is only an effect, a construction, of relationships between people, meaning that its objective character is contestable.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] In common parlance, property rights involve a bundle of rights including occupancy, use and enjoyment, and the right to sell, devise, give, or lease all or part of these rights.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Custodians of property have obligations as well as rights.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Menon claims that the autonomous individual, responsible for his/her own existence, is a cultural construct moulded by Western culture rather than the truth about the human condition.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Penner views property as an "illusion"—a "normative phantasm" without substance.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] In the neoliberal literature, the property is part of the private side of a public/private dichotomy and acts as a counterweight to state power.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Davies counters that "any space may be subject to plural meanings or appropriations which do not necessarily come into conflict".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Private property has never been a universal doctrine, although since the end of the Cold War, it has become nearly so.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Some societies, e.g., Native American bands, held land, if not all property, in common.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] When groups came into conflict, the victor often appropriated the loser's property.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The rights paradigm tended to stabilize the distribution of property holdings on the presumption that title had been lawfully acquired.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Property does not exist in isolation, and neither do property rights.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Bryan claimed that property rights describe relations among people and not just relations between people and things.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Singer holds that the idea that owners have no legal obligations to others wrongly supposes that property rights hardly ever conflict with other legally protected interests.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Singer continues implying that legal realists "did not take the character and structure of social relations as an important independent factor in choosing the rules that govern market life".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The ethics of property rights begins with recognizing the vacuous nature of the notion of property.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Intellectual property (IP) encompasses expressions of ideas, thoughts, codes, and information.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] "Intellectual property rights" (IPR) treat IP as a kind of real property, subject to analogous protections, rather than as a reproducible good or service.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Boldrin and Levine argue that "government does not ordinarily enforce monopolies for producers of other goods.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] This is because it is widely recognized that a monopoly creates many social costs.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Intellectual monopoly is no different in this respect.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] International standards relating to intellectual property rights are enforced through the Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] In the US, IP other than copyrights is regulated by the United States Patent and Trademark Office.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The US Constitution included the power to protect intellectual property, empowering the Federal government "to promote the progress of science and useful arts, by securing for limited times to authors and inventors the exclusive right to their respective writings and discoveries".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Boldrin and Levine see no value in such state-enforced monopolies, stating, "we ordinarily think of innovative monopoly as an oxymoron.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Further, they comment, 'intellectual property' "is not like ordinary property at all, but constitutes a government grant of a costly and dangerous private monopoly over ideas.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] We show through theory and example that intellectual monopoly is not necessary for innovation and, as a practical matter, is damaging to growth, prosperity, and liberty".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Steelman defends patent monopolies, writing, "Consider prescription drugs, for instance.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Such drugs have benefited millions of people, improving or extending their lives.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] One attack on IPR is moral rather than utilitarian, claiming that inventions are mostly a collective, cumulative, path-dependent, social creation and therefore, no one person or firm should be able to monopolize them even for a limited period.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The opposing argument is that the benefits of innovation arrive sooner when patents encourage innovators and their investors to increase their commitments.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Machlup concluded that patents do not have the intended effect of enhancing innovation.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Mindeli and Pipiya argued that the knowledge economy is an economy of abundance because it relies on the "infinite potential" of knowledge and ideas rather than on the limited resources of natural resources, labor and capital.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Allison envisioned an egalitarian distribution of knowledge.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Kinsella claimed that IPR create artificial scarcity and reduce equality.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Bouckaert wrote, "Natural scarcity is that which follows from the relationship between man and nature.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Scarcity is natural when it is possible to conceive of it before any human, institutional, or contractual arrangement.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Artificial scarcity, on the other hand, is the outcome of such arrangements.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Artificial scarcity can hardly serve as a justification for the legal framework that causes that scarcity.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Such an argument would be completely circular.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] On the contrary, artificial scarcity itself needs a justification".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Corporations fund much IP creation and can acquire IP they do not create, to which Menon and others have objected.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Andersen claims that IPR has increasingly become an instrument in eroding the public domain.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Notable IP copyright cases include *A&M Records, Inc. v.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Ashcroft*, and Disney's lawsuit against the Air Pirates.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] While business ethics emerged as a field in the 1970s, international business ethics did not emerge until the late 1990s, looking back on the international developments of that decade.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Many new practical issues arose out of the international context of business.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Theoretical issues such as the cultural relativity of ethical values receive more emphasis in this field.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Other, older issues can be grouped here as well.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Foreign countries often use dumping as a competitive threat, selling products at prices lower than their normal value.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] This can lead to problems in domestic markets, as it becomes difficult for them to compete with the pricing set by foreign markets.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] In 2009, the International Trade Commission conducted research on anti-dumping laws.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Dumping is often seen as an ethical issue, as larger companies take advantage of other, less economically advanced companies.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Ethical issues often arise in business settings, whether through business transactions or forming new business relationships.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] It also has a huge focus in the auditing field, whereby the type of verification can be directly dictated by ethical theory.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] An ethical issue in a business atmosphere may refer to any situation that requires business associates as individuals, or as a group (for example, a department or firm) to evaluate the morality of specific actions, and subsequently, make a decision among the choices.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Some ethical issues of particular concern in today's evolving business market include such topics as honesty, integrity, professional behaviors, environmental issues, harassment, and fraud, to name a few.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The ethical issues associated with honesty are widespread and vary greatly in business, from the misuse of company time or resources to lying with malicious intent, engaging in bribery, or creating conflicts of interest within an organization.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Honesty encompasses the truthful speech and actions of an individual wholly.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Some cultures and belief systems even consider honesty to be an essential pillar of life, such as Confucianism and Buddhism (referred to as sacca, part of the Four Noble Truths).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Many employees lie in order to reach goals, avoid assignments or negative issues; however, sacrificing honesty in order to gain status or reap rewards poses potential problems for the overall ethical culture organization, and jeopardizes organizational goals in the long run.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Using company time or resources for personal use is also commonly viewed as unethical because it boils down to stealing from the company.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The misuse of resources costs companies billions of dollars each year, averaging about 4.25 hours per week of stolen time alone, and employees' abuse of Internet services is another main concern.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Bribery, on the other hand, is not only considered unethical in business practices, but it is also illegal.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] In accordance with this, the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act was established in 1977 to deter international businesses from giving or receiving unwarranted payments and gifts that were intended to influence the decisions of executives and political officials.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Although small payments known as facilitation payments will not be considered unlawful under the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act if they are used towards regular public governance activities, such as permits or licenses.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Many aspects of the work environment influence an individual's decision-making regarding ethics in the business world.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] When an individual is on the path of growing a company, many outside influences can pressure them to perform a certain way.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The core of a person's performance in the workplace is rooted in their personal code of behavior.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] A person's personal code of ethics encompasses many different qualities such as integrity, honesty, communication, respect, compassion, and common goals.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] In addition, the ethical standards set forth by a person's superior(s) often translate into their own code of ethics.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The company's policy is the 'umbrella' of ethics that plays a major role in the personal development and decision-making processes that people make with respect to ethical behavior.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] National economic conditions often shape corporate ethics.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] In environments marked by high poverty, large corporations may continue to expand, while smaller firms face significant survival challenges.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] This pressure can lead leadership to explore unconventional or unethical avenues to secure business opportunities.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Similarly, social media has become a primary influence on ethical standards.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The constant flow of information and public opinion can pressure individuals to conform to perceived norms.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Consequently, fast-moving digital trends and the drive for instant engagement can alter how people evaluate moral and professional decisions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Political economy and political philosophy have ethical implications, particularly regarding the distribution of economic benefits.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] John Rawls and Robert Nozick are both notable contributors.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] For example, Rawls has been interpreted as offering a critique of offshore outsourcing on social contract grounds.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Laws are the written statutes, codes, and opinions of government organizations by which citizens, businesses, and persons present within a jurisdiction are expected to govern themselves or face legal sanction.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Sanctions for violating the law can include (a) civil penalties, such as fines, pecuniary damages, and loss of licenses, property, rights, or privileges; (b) criminal penalties, such as fines, probation, imprisonment, or a combination thereof; or (c) both civil and criminal penalties.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Very often, it is held that business is not bound by any ethics other than abiding by the law.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Milton Friedman is the pioneer of the view.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] He held that corporations have the obligation to make a profit within the framework of the legal system, nothing more.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Friedman made it explicit that the duty of the business leaders is "to make as much money as possible while conforming to the basic rules of the society, both those embodied in the law and those embodied in ethical custom".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Ethics for Friedman is nothing more than abiding by customs and laws.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] The reduction of ethics to abidance to laws and customs, however, has drawn serious criticisms.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Counter to Friedman's logic, it is observed that legal procedures are technocratic, bureaucratic, rigid and obligatory whereas ethical act is conscientious, voluntary choice beyond normativity.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] For Law against crime to be passed, the crime must have happened.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Laws are blind to the crimes undefined in them.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Further, as per law, "conduct is not criminal unless forbidden by law which gives advance warning that such conduct is criminal".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Also, the law presumes the accused is innocent until proven guilty and that the state must establish the guilt of the accused beyond a reasonable doubt.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] As per liberal laws followed in most of the democracies, until the government prosecutor proves the firm guilty with the limited resources available to her, the accused is considered to be innocent.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p01] Though the liberal premises of law are necessary to protect individuals from being persecuted by the government, it is not a sufficient mechanism to make firms morally accountable.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] As part of more comprehensive compliance and ethics programs, many companies have formulated internal policies pertaining to the ethical conduct of employees.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] These policies can be simple exhortations in broad, highly generalized language (typically called a corporate ethics statement), or they can be more detailed policies, containing specific behavioral requirements (typically called corporate ethics codes).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] They are generally meant to identify the company's expectations of workers and to offer guidance on handling some of the more common ethical problems that might arise in the course of doing business.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] It is hoped that having such a policy will lead to greater ethical awareness, consistency in application, and the avoidance of ethical disasters.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] An increasing number of companies also require employees to attend seminars regarding business conduct, which often include discussion of the company's policies, specific case studies, and legal requirements.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Some companies even require their employees to sign agreements stating that they will abide by the company's rules of conduct.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Many companies are assessing the environmental factors that can lead employees to engage in unethical conduct.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] A competitive business environment may call for unethical behavior.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Lying has become expected in fields such as trading.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] An example of this is the issues surrounding the unethical actions of the Salomon Brothers.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Not everyone supports corporate policies that govern ethical conduct.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Some claim that ethical problems are better dealt with by depending upon employees to use their own judgment.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Others believe that corporate ethics policies are primarily rooted in utilitarian concerns and that they are mainly to limit the company's legal liability or to curry public favor by giving the appearance of being a good corporate citizen.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Ideally, the company will avoid a lawsuit because its employees will follow the rules.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Should a lawsuit occur, the company can claim that the problem would not have arisen if the employee had only followed the code properly.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Some corporations have tried to burnish their ethical image by creating whistle-blower protections, such as anonymity.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] In the case of Citi, they call this the Ethics Hotline.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Though it is unclear whether firms such as Citi take offences reported to these hotlines seriously or not.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Sometimes there is a disconnection between the company's code of ethics and the company's actual practices.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Thus, whether or not such conduct is explicitly sanctioned by management, at worst, this makes the policy duplicitous, and, at best, it is merely a marketing tool.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Jones and Parker wrote, "Most of what we read under the name business ethics is either sentimental common sense or a set of excuses for being unpleasant." Many manuals are procedural form-filling exercises, unconcerned about the real ethical dilemmas.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] For instance, the US Department of Commerce ethics program treats business ethics as a set of instructions and procedures to be followed by 'ethics officers'.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Some others claim that being ethical is just for the sake of being ethical.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Business ethicists may trivialize the subject, offering standard answers that do not reflect the situation's complexity.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Ethics codes often state a company's view on DEI (diversity, equity, inclusivity).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] In 2025, some companies began changing their ethics policies to reduce the focus on DEI, and some companies have decided to completely eliminate DEI from their policies.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Following a series of fraud, corruption, and abuse scandals that affected the United States defense industry in the mid-1980s, the Defense Industry Initiative (DII) was created to promote ethical business practices and ethics management in multiple industries.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Subsequent to these scandals, many organizations began appointing ethics officers (also referred to as "compliance" officers).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] In 1991, the Ethics & Compliance Officer Association —originally the Ethics Officer Association (EOA)—was founded at the Center for Business Ethics at Bentley University as a professional association for ethics and compliance officers.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] The 1991 passing of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines for Organizations in 1991 was another factor in many companies appointing ethics/compliance officers.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] These guidelines, intended to assist judges with sentencing, set standards organizations must follow to obtain a reduction in sentence if they are convicted of a federal offense.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Following the high-profile corporate scandals of companies like Enron, WorldCom and Tyco between 2001 and 2004, and following the passage of the Sarbanes–Oxley Act, many small and mid-sized companies also began to appoint ethics officers.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Often reporting to the chief executive officer, ethics officers focus on uncovering or preventing unethical and illegal actions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] This is accomplished by assessing the ethical implications of the company's activities, making recommendations on ethical policies, and disseminating information to employees.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] The effectiveness of ethics officers is not clear.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] The establishment of an ethics officer position is likely to be insufficient in driving ethical business practices without a corporate culture that values ethical behavior.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] These values and behaviors should be consistently and systemically supported by those at the top of the organization.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Employees with strong community involvement, loyalty to employers, superiors or owners, smart work practices, and trust among the team members do inculcate a corporate culture.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Many corporate and business strategies now include sustainability.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] In addition to the traditional environmental 'green' sustainability concerns, business ethics practices have expanded to include social sustainability.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Social sustainability focuses on issues related to human capital in the business supply chain, such as workers' rights, working conditions, child labor, and human trafficking.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Incorporation of these considerations is increasing, as consumers and procurement officials demand documentation of a business's compliance with national and international initiatives, guidelines, and standards.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Initiatives in sustainability encompass "green" topics, as well as social sustainability.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Tao *et al*. refer to a variety of "green" business practices, including green strategy, green design, green production and green operation.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] There are however, many different ways in which sustainability initiatives can be implemented by a company.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] An organization can implement sustainability initiatives by improving its operations and manufacturing processes so as to make it more aligned with environmental, social, and governance issues.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Walmart has made commitments to doubling its truck fleet efficiency by 2015 by replacing 2/3rds of its fleet with more fuel-efficient trucks, including hybrids.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Dell has integrated alternative, recycled, and recyclable materials in its products and packaging design, improving energy efficiency and design for end-of-life and recyclability.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Dell plans to reduce the energy intensity of its product portfolio by 80% by 2020.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] The board of a company can decide to lower executive compensation by a given percentage, and give the percentage of compensation to a specific cause.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] This is an effort which can only be implemented from the top, as it will affect the compensation of all executives in the company.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] In Alcoa, an aluminum company based in the US, "1/5th of executive cash compensation is tied to safety, diversity, and environmental stewardship, which includes greenhouse gas emission reductions and energy efficiency" (Best Practices).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] This is not usually the case for most companies, where we see the board take a uniform step towards the environment, social, and governance issues.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] This is only the case for companies that are directly linked to utilities, energy, or material industries, something which Alcoa as an aluminum company, falls in line with.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Instead, formal committees focused on the environment, social, and governance issues are more usually seen in governance committees and audit committees, rather than the board of directors.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] "According to research analysis done by Pearl Meyer in support of the NACD 2017 Director Compensation Report shows that among 1,400 public companies reviewed, only slightly more than five percent of boards have a designated committee to address ESG issues." (How compensation can).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Similar to board leadership, creating steering committees and other types of committees specialized for sustainability, senior executives are identified who are held accountable for meeting and constantly improving sustainability goals.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Introducing bonus schemes that reward executives for meeting non-financial performance, goals including safety targets, greenhouse gas emissions, reduction targets, and goals engaging stakeholders to help shape the company's public policy positions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Companies such as Exelon have implemented policies like this.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Other companies will keep sustainability within their strategy and goals, presenting findings at shareholder meetings, and actively tracking metrics on sustainability.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Companies such as PepsiCo, Heineken, and FIFCO take steps in this direction to implement sustainability initiatives.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Companies such as Coca-Cola have actively tried to improve their efficiency of water usage, hiring 3rd party auditors to evaluate their water management approach.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] FIFCO has also successfully led water-management initiatives.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Implementation of sustainability projects through directly appealing to employees (typically through the human resource department) is another option for companies to implement sustainability.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] This involves integrating sustainability into the company culture, with hiring practices and employee training.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] General Electric is a company that is taking the lead in implementing initiatives in this manner.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Bank of America directly engaged employees by implementing LEED (Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design) certified buildings, with a fifth of its building meeting these certifications.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Establishing requirements for not only internal operations but also first-tier suppliers as well as second-tier suppliers to help drive environmental and social expectations further down the supply chain.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Companies such as Starbucks, FIFCO and Ford Motor Company have implemented requirements that suppliers must meet to win their business.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Starbucks has led efforts in engaging suppliers and local communities where they operate to accelerate investment in sustainable farming.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Starbucks set a goal of ethically sourcing 100% of its coffee beans by 2015.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] By revealing decision-making data about how sustainability was reached, companies can give away insights that can help others across the industry and beyond make more sustainable decisions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Nike launched its "making app" in 2013, which released data about the sustainability of the materials it was using.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] This ultimately allows other companies to make more sustainable design decisions and create lower-impact products.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] As an academic discipline, business ethics emerged in the 1970s.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Since no academic business ethics journals or conferences existed, researchers published in general management journals and attended general conferences.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Over time, specialized peer-reviewed journals appeared, and more researchers entered the field.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Corporate scandals in the early 2000s increased the field's popularity.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] As of 2009, sixteen academic journals devoted to various business ethics issues existed, with *Journal of Business Ethics* and *Business Ethics Quarterly* considered the leaders.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] *Journal of Business Ethics Education* publishes articles specifically about education in business ethics.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] The International Business Development Institute is a global non-profit organization that represents 217 nations and all 50 United States.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] It offers a Charter in Business Development that focuses on ethical business practices and standards.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] The Charter is directed by Harvard University, MIT, and Fulbright Scholars, and it includes graduate-level coursework in economics, politics, marketing, management, technology, and legal aspects of business development as it pertains to business ethics.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] IBDI also oversees the International Business Development Institute of Asia, which provides individuals living in 20 Asian nations the opportunity to earn the Charter.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] In Sharia law, followed by many Muslims, banking specifically prohibits charging interest on loans.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Traditional Confucian thought discourages profit-seeking.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] According to the article "Theory of the real economy", there is a narrower point of view from the Christian faith towards the relationship between ethics and religious traditions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] This article stresses how Christianity is capable of establishing reliable boundaries for financial institutions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Business ethics receives an extensive treatment in Jewish thought and Rabbinic literature, both from an ethical (*Mussar*) and a legal (*Halakha*) perspective; see the article *Jewish business ethics* for further discussion.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] According to the article "Indian Philosophy and Business Ethics: A Review", by Chandrani Chattopadyay, Hindus follow "Dharma" as Business Ethics and unethical business practices are termed "Adharma".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Businessmen are supposed to maintain steadiness, self-purification, non-violence, concentration, clarity and control over their senses.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Books like the Bhagavat Gita and the Arthashastra contribute a lot towards the conduct of ethical business.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Business ethics is related to philosophy of economics, the branch of the philosophy that deals with the philosophical, political, and ethical underpinnings of business and economics.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Business ethics is also related to political economy, which is an economic analysis from political and historical perspectives.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/business-ethics-p02] Political economy deals with the distributive consequences of economic actions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] There are considerable variations in the composition and responsibilities of corporate titles.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Typically, senior managers are "higher" than vice presidents, although many times a senior officer may also hold a vice president title, such as executive vice president and chief financial officer (CFO).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] The board of directors is technically not part of management itself, although its chairman may be considered part of the corporate office if he or she is an executive chairman.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] A corporation often consists of different businesses, whose senior executives report directly to the CEO or COO, but that depends on the form of the business.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] If organized as a division then the top manager is often known as an executive vice president (EVP).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] If that business is a subsidiary which has considerably more independence, then the title might be chairman and CEO.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] In many countries, particularly in Europe and Asia, there is a separate executive board for day-to-day business and supervisory board (elected by shareholders) for control purposes.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] In these countries, the CEO presides over the executive board and the chairman presides over the supervisory board, and these two roles will always be held by different people.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] This ensures a distinction between management by the executive board and governance by the supervisory board.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] This seemingly allows for clear lines of authority.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] There is a strong parallel here with the structure of government, which tends to separate the political cabinet from the management civil service.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Morgan Chase), management committee (Goldman Sachs), executive committee (Lehman Brothers), executive council (Hewlett-Packard), or executive board (HeiG) composed of the division/subsidiary heads and senior officers that report directly to the CEO.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Section 149 of the Companies Act 2013 mandates a board of directors for each company regardless of its size.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] The same act mandates that the share certificates must be signed by two officers with titles specified by law (e.g. a two directors or a director and company secretary).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] State laws in the United States traditionally required certain positions to be created within every corporation, such as president, secretary and treasurer.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Today, the approach under the *Model Business Corporation Act*, which is employed in many states, is to grant corporations discretion in determining which titles to have, with the only mandated organ being the board of directors.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Some states that do not employ the MBCA continue to require that certain offices be established.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Under the law of Delaware, where most large US corporations are established, stock certificates must be signed by two officers with titles specified by law (e.g. a president and secretary or a president and treasurer).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Every corporation incorporated in California must have a chairman of the board or a president (or both), as well as a secretary and a chief financial officer.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Limited liability company (LLC)-structured companies are generally run directly by their members, but the members can agree to appoint officers such as a CEO or to appoint "managers" to operate the company.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] American companies are generally led by a CEO.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] In some companies, the CEO also has the title of "president".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] In other companies, a president is a different person, and the primary duties of the two positions are defined in the company's bylaws (or the laws of the governing legal jurisdiction).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Many companies also have a CFO, a COO and other senior positions such as chief legal officer (CLO), chief strategy officer (CSO), chief marketing officer (CMO), etc. that report to the president and CEO.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] The next level, which are not executive positions, is middle management and may be called "vice presidents", "directors" or "managers", depending on the size and required managerial depth of the company.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] In British English, the title of managing director is broadly synonymous with that of chief executive officer.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Managing directors do not have any particular authority under the *Companies Act* in the UK, but do have implied authority based on the general understanding of what their position entails, as well as any authority expressly delegated by the board of directors.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] In Japan, corporate titles are roughly standardized across companies and organizations; although there is variation from company to company, corporate titles within a company are always consistent, and the large companies in Japan generally follow the same outline.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] These titles are the formal titles that are used on business cards.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Korean corporate titles are similar to those of Japan.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Legally, Japanese and Korean companies are only required to have a board of directors with at least one representative director.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] In Japanese, a company director is called a *torishimariyaku* (取締役) and a representative director is called a *daihyō torishimariyaku* (代表取締役).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] The equivalent Korean titles are *isa* (이사, 理事) and *daepyo-isa* (대표이사, 代表理事).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] These titles are often combined with lower titles, e.g.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] *senmu torishimariyaku* or *jōmu torishimariyaku* for Japanese executives who are also board members.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Most Japanese companies also have statutory auditors, who operate alongside the board of directors in supervisory roles.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Under the commercial code in Japan, *Jugyōin* (従業員) meaning the "employee", is different from *Kaishain* (会社員), meaning the "stockholders".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] The top management group, comprising *jomu*/*sangmu* and above, is often referred to collectively as "cadre" or "senior management" (幹部 or 重役; *kambu* or *juyaku* in Japanese; *ganbu* or *jungyŏk* in Korean).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Some Japanese and Korean companies have also adopted American-style titles, but these are not yet widespread and their usage varies.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Since the late 1990s, many Japanese companies have introduced the title of *shikkō yakuin* (執行役員) or 'officer', seeking to emulate the separation of directors and officers found in American companies.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] In 2002, the statutory title of *shikkō yaku* (執行役) was introduced for use in companies that introduced a three-committee structure in their board of directors.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] The titles are frequently given to *buchō* and higher-level personnel.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] *Shikkō yakuin* are considered employees of the company that follow the decisions of the board of directors, although in some cases directors may have the *shikkō yakuin* title as well.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] The highest-level executives in senior management usually have titles beginning with "chief" and ending with "officer", forming what is often called the "C-suite", or "CxO", where "x" is a variable that could be any functional area (not to be confused with CXO).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] The traditional three such officers are CEO, COO, and CFO.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Depending on the management structure, titles may exist instead of, or be blended/overlapped with, other traditional executive titles, such as *president*, various designations of *vice presidents* (e.g.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] VP of marketing), and *general managers* or *directors* of various divisions (such as director of marketing); the latter may or may not imply membership of the *board of directors*.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Certain other prominent positions have emerged, some of which are sector-specific.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] For example, chief audit executive (CAE), chief procurement officer (CPO) and chief risk officer (CRO) positions are often found in many types of financial services companies.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Technology companies of all sorts now tend to have a chief technology officer (CTO) to manage technology development.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] A chief information officer (CIO) oversees information technology (IT) matters, either in companies that specialize in IT or in any kind of company that relies on it for supporting infrastructure.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Many companies now also have a chief marketing officer (CMO), particularly mature companies in competitive sectors, where brand management is a high priority.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] A chief value officer (CVO) is introduced in companies where business processes and organizational entities are focused on the creation and maximization of value.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Approximately 50% of the S&P 500 companies have created a chief strategy officer (CSO) in their top management team to lead strategic planning and manage inorganic growth, which provides a long range perspective versus the tactical view of the COO or CFO.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] This function often replaces a COO on the C-Suite team, in cases where the company wants to focus on growth rather than efficiency and cost containment.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] A chief administrative officer (CAO) may be found in many large complex organizations that have various departments or divisions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Additionally, many companies now call their top diversity leadership position the chief diversity officer (CDO).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] However, this and many other nontraditional and lower-ranking titles are not universally recognized as corporate officers, and they tend to be specific to particular organizational cultures or the preferences of employees.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] Chairman of the board – presiding officer of the corporate board of directors.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/c-suite] The chairman influences the board of directors, which in turn elects and removes the officers of a corporation and oversees the human, financial, environmental and technical operations of a corporation.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/central-bank-of-brazil] The **Central Bank of Brazil** (**BCB**; Portuguese: *Banco Central do Brasil*, pronounced [ˈbɐ̃ku sẽˈtɾaw du bɾaˈziw]) is the central bank of Brazil.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/central-bank-of-brazil] It is the country's chief monetary authority and is responsible for maintaining the stability of the national currency's purchasing power.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/central-bank-of-brazil] The bank was established on 31 December 1964.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/central-bank-of-brazil] The Central Bank of Brazil is not affiliated with any ministry and, like other central banks, exercises monetary authority in the country.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/central-bank-of-brazil] It was created through the merger of three institutions: the Superintendência da Moeda e do Crédito (SUMOC), the Bank of Brazil (BB), and the National Treasury.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/central-bank-of-brazil] One of the main instruments of Brazil's monetary policy is the bank's benchmark overnight interest rate, known as the SELIC rate, which is set by the bank's Monetary Policy Committee (Copom).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/central-bank-of-brazil] The bank is also active in promoting financial inclusion and is a leading member of the Alliance for Financial Inclusion.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/central-bank-of-brazil] It was one of the original 17 regulatory institutions to make national commitments to financial inclusion under the Maya Declaration.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/central-bank-of-brazil] Since 25 February 2021, the bank has been institutionally independent from the federal government.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/central-bank-of-brazil] On 3 November 2020, the bill of the Independence of Central Bank passed the Senate, by 56 votes to 12.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/central-bank-of-brazil] And on 10 February 2021, in the Chamber of Deputies was approved by 339 votes in favor and 114 against without changes, going to President Jair Bolsonaro's sanction, generating the Federal Complementary Law No.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/central-bank-of-brazil] 179 of 24 February 2021, it became autonomous, in addition to gaining a new organizational structure.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] The **chair**, also **chairman**, **chairwoman**, or **chairperson**, is the presiding officer of an organized group such as a board, committee, or deliberative assembly.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] The person holding the office, who is typically elected or appointed by members of the group or organisation, presides over meetings of the group, and is required to conduct the group's business in an orderly fashion.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] In some organizations, the chair is also known as *president* (or other title).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] In others, where a board appoints a president (or other title), the two terms are used for distinct positions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] The term chairman may be used in a neutral manner, not directly implying the gender of the holder.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] In meetings or conferences, to "chair" something (chairing) means to lead the event.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] Terms for the office and its holder include *chair*, *chairman*, *chairwoman*, *chairperson*, *convenor*, *facilitator*, *moderator*, *president*, and *presiding officer*.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] The chair of a parliamentary chamber is sometimes called the *speaker*.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] *Chair* has been used to refer to a seat or office of authority since the middle of the 17th century; its earliest citation in the *Oxford English Dictionary* dates to 1658–1659, four years after the first citation for *chairman*.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] Feminist critiques have analysed *Chairman* as a possible example of sexist language, associating the male gender with the exercise of authority; this has led to some use of the generic "Chairperson".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] In World Schools Style debating, as of 2009, *chair* or *chairman* refers to the person who controls the debate; it recommends using *Madame Chair* or *Mr.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] The *FranklinCovey Style Guide for Business and Technical Communication* and the American Psychological Association style guide advocate using *chair* or *chairperson*.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] *The Oxford Dictionary of American Usage and Style* (2000) suggested that the gender-neutral forms were gaining ground; it advocated *chair* for both men and women.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] *The Daily Telegraph*'s style guide bans the use of *chair* and *chairperson*; the newspaper's position, as of 2018, is that "chairman is correct English".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] The National Association of Parliamentarians adopted a resolution in 1975 discouraging the use of *chairperson* and rescinded it in 2017.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] The word *chair* can refer to the place from which the holder of the office presides, whether on a chair, at a lectern, or elsewhere.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] During meetings, the person presiding is said to be "in the chair" and is also referred to as "the chair".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] Parliamentary procedure requires that members address the "chair" as "Mr.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] (or Madam) Chairman (or Chair or Chairperson)" rather than using a name – one of many customs intended to maintain the presiding officer's impartiality and to ensure an objective and impersonal approach.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] In the British music hall tradition, the chairman was the master of ceremonies who announced the performances and was responsible for controlling any rowdy elements in the audience.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] The role was popularised on British TV in the 1960s and 1970s by Leonard Sachs, the chairman on the variety show *The Good Old Days*.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] "Chairman" as a quasi-title gained particular resonance when socialist states from 1917 onwards shunned more traditional leadership labels and stressed the collective control of *Soviets* (councils or committees) by beginning to refer to executive figureheads as "Chairman of the X Committee".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] Vladimir Lenin, for example, officially functioned as the head of Soviet Russian government not as prime minister or as president, but as "Chairman of the Council of People's Commissars".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] At the same time, the head of the state was first called "Chairman of the Central Executive Committee" (until 1938) and then "Chairman of the Presidium of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet".
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] In China, Mao Zedong was commonly called "Chairman Mao", as he was officially Chairman of the Chinese Communist Party and Chairman of the Central Military Commission.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] In addition to the administrative or executive duties in organizations, the chair presides over meetings.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] While presiding, the chair should remain impartial and not interrupt a speaker if the speaker has the floor and is following the rules of the group.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] In committees or small boards, the chair votes along with the other members; in assemblies or larger boards, the chair should vote only when it can affect the result.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] At a meeting, the chair only has one vote (i.e. the chair cannot vote twice and cannot override the decision of the group unless the organization has specifically given the chair such authority).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] The powers of the chair vary widely across organizations.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] In some organizations they have the authority to hire staff and make financial decisions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] In others they only make recommendations to a board of directors, or may have no executive powers, in which case they are mainly a spokesperson for the organization.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] The power given depends upon the type of organization, its structure, and the rules it has created for itself.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] If the chair exceeds their authority, engages in misconduct, or fails to perform their duties, they may face disciplinary procedures.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] Such procedures may include censure, suspension, or removal from office.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] The rules of the organization would provide details on who can perform these disciplinary procedures.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] Usually, whoever appointed or elected the chair has the power to discipline them.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] There are three common types of chair in public corporations.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] The chief executive officer (CEO) may also hold the title of chair, in which case the board frequently names an independent member of the board as a lead independent director.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] This position is equivalent to the position of président-directeur général in France.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] Executive chair is an office separate from that of CEO, where the titleholder wields influence over company operations, such as Larry Ellison of Oracle, Douglas Flint of HSBC and Steve Case of AOL Time Warner, Jeff Bezos of Amazon, Ignacio Sánchez Galán of Iberdrola and Ana Botín of Banco Santander.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] In particular, the group chair of HSBC is considered the top position of that institution, outranking the chief executive, and is responsible for leading the board and representing the company in meetings with government figures.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] Before the creation of the group management board in 2006, HSBC's chair essentially held the duties of a chief executive at an equivalent institution, while HSBC's chief executive served as the deputy.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] After the 2006 reorganization, the management cadre ran the business, while the chair oversaw the controls of the business through compliance and audit and the direction of the business.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] Non-executive chair is also a separate post from the CEO; unlike an executive chair, a non-executive chair does not interfere in day-to-day company matters.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] Across the world, many companies have separated the roles of chair and CEO, saying that this move improves corporate governance.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] Many companies in the US have an executive chair; this method of organization is sometimes called the American model.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] Having a non-executive chair is common in the UK and Canada; this is sometimes called the British model.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] Expert opinion is rather evenly divided over which is the preferable model.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] There is a growing push by public market investors for companies with an executive chair to have a lead independent director to provide some element of an independent perspective.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] The role of the chair in a private equity-backed board differs from the role in non-profit or publicly listed organizations in several ways, including the pay, role and what makes an effective private-equity chair.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] Companies with both an executive chair and a CEO include Ford, HSBC, Alphabet Inc., and HP.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] A vice- or deputy chair, subordinate to the chair, is sometimes chosen to assist and to serve as chair in the latter's absence, or when a motion involving the chair is being discussed.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] In the absence of the chair and vice-chair, groups sometimes elect a *chair pro tempore* to fill the role for a single meeting.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] In some organizations that have both titles, deputy chair ranks higher than vice-chair, as there are often multiple vice-chairs but only a single deputy chair.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] This type of deputy chair title on its own usually has only an advisory role and not an operational one (such as Ted Turner at Time Warner).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chair-officer] An unrelated definition of vice- and deputy chairs describes an executive who is higher ranking or has more seniority than an executive vice-president (EVP).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] The **chief compliance officer** (**CCO**) is a corporate executive within the C-suite responsible for overseeing and managing regulatory compliance issues within an organization.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] The CCO typically reports to the chief executive officer or the chief legal officer.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] Several countries around the world have enacted regulations that require organizations to appoint **Compliance Officers** as a means of ensuring adherence to legal and regulatory frameworks.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] This section highlights some of the primary jurisdictions where the appointment of a Compliance Officer is mandatory, with a focus on the financial sector, where such requirements are particularly prevalent.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] In the United States, the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) mandates that certain financial institutions designate a Compliance Officer who is responsible for implementing and maintaining an effective Anti-Money Laundering (AML) program.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] Additionally, the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act and the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) regulations require registered investment advisers to appoint a Chief Compliance Officer (CCO) to ensure compliance with federal securities laws.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] In the European Union, the Fourth Anti-Money Laundering Directive (4AMLD) stipulates that organizations subject to AML and Counter-Terrorist Financing (CTF) requirements must designate a Compliance Officer at the management level.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] Additionally, the Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID II) imposes an obligation on investment firms to appoint a Compliance Officer responsible for ensuring compliance with the regulatory requirements set out in the directive.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] In Brazil, the Central Bank of Brazil (BACEN) requires financial institutions to have a Compliance Officer to oversee the management of compliance risk and ensure adherence to applicable regulations.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] Similarly, in India, the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) mandates that banks appoint a Chief Compliance Officer to oversee compliance with banking regulations and guidelines.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] In Chile, companies are required to have a *Crime Prevention Officer* who fulfills the role of a Compliance Officer, as they manage the Crime Prevention Model within the framework of the Corporate crime Liability (Ley 20.393).
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] This law holds legal entities accountable for crimes such as money laundering, terrorist financing, and bribery, among others.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] The Crime Prevention Officer is responsible for implementing and supervising the company's compliance program to prevent and detect the commission of these crimes.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] Furthermore, for entities subject to reporting obligations concerning potential money laundering or terrorist financing operations, the appointment of a Compliance Officer is mandatory.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] These measures are in line with Chile's commitment to combat economic crimes, ensuring corporate transparency, and fostering a culture of compliance within the country.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] These examples demonstrate the global trend towards mandating the appointment of Compliance Officers, particularly within the financial sector, as a means of promoting legal and regulatory compliance, preventing financial crimes, and fostering a culture of ethical behavior within organizations.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] Chief compliance officers can play a crucial role in stopping the global escalation of corruption, money laundering, and other economic crimes that deeply corrode societies, especially in less developed regions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] By ensuring that companies adhere to legal and ethical standards, CCOs can contribute to building fairer societies and promoting good corporate citizenship.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] Companies that prioritize compliance and corporate social responsibility can help create a more transparent and accountable business environment, which in turn fosters economic growth and social development.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] As a result of rising wages the need for outsourcing compliance has increased according to a 2024 compliance study.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] The Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) were established by the United Nations in 2015 as a framework for addressing pressing global challenges.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] As guardians of regulatory compliance and ethical conduct, compliance officers contribute to the realization of SDG 16 by ensuring that organizations comply with applicable laws, regulations, and best practices.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] This fosters a culture of integrity and ethical behavior within organizations, which in turn helps to reduce corruption, promote fair competition, and support the development of strong, accountable institutions.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] By mitigating risks associated with economic crimes, such as money laundering, fraud, and bribery, compliance officers work to create a more stable and just business environment, enabling the broader goals of peace and sustainable development.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] Furthermore, compliance officers play a significant role in upholding the rule of law and ensuring access to justice, as outlined in SDG 16.3.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] By implementing robust internal controls and procedures, they assist in detecting and preventing illegal activities, thereby contributing to the enforcement of laws and the prevention of crime.
[src:chief-compliance-officer/chief-compliance-officer] Additionally, compliance officers serve as intermediaries between organizations and regulatory authorities, facilitating cooperation and communication to address compliance issues and promote transparency in business operations.
